==Variants==
[[File:XM1113 in flight.jpg|thumb|XM1113 extended-range artillery round, shown here at a range demonstration, uses a rocket-assist motor.]]
*'''M777A2''' – Block 1A software upgrade. Addition of an Enhanced Portable Inductive Artillery Fuze Setter (EPIAFS) to enable [[M982 Excalibur|Excalibur]] and precision munition compatibility.<ref name="Goldman" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Gooding |first1=Keith |last2=Kratzer |first2=David |date=October–December 2008 |title=PEO GCS's Digitized Towed Howitzer Supports the GWOT |url=https://asc.army.mil/docs/pubs/alt/2008/4_OctNovDec/articles/32_PEO_GCS's_Digitized_Towed_Howitzer_Supports_the_GWOT_200810.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110232243/http://asc.army.mil/docs/pubs/alt/2008/4_OctNovDec/articles/32_PEO_GCS%27s_Digitized_Towed_Howitzer_Supports_the_GWOT_200810.pdf |archive-date=10 November 2013 |access-date=27 January 2013 |work=Army Acquisition, Logistics, and Technology Magazine |publisher=US Army Acquisition Support Center |page=32}}</ref>
* '''M777ER''' – Upgrade created by the Extended Range Cannon Artillery (ERCA) project to extend range from {{convert|30|to|70|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref>[https://www.armyrecognition.com/weapons_defence_industry_military_technology_uk/u.s._army_engineers_work_to_create_a_new_longer_m777_155mm_howitzer_under_the_name_m777er_13103162.html U.S. Army engineers work to create a new longer M777 155mm howitzer under the name M777ER] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180325052123/https://www.armyrecognition.com/weapons_defence_industry_military_technology_uk/u.s._army_engineers_work_to_create_a_new_longer_m777_155mm_howitzer_under_the_name_m777er_13103162.html|date=25 March 2018}}. ''Army Recognition''. 31 March 2016.</ref> Modified with a longer 55-caliber, {{cvt|30|ft|m|order=flip}} barrel and supercharged propellant firing the XM1113 [[rocket-assisted projectile]].<ref>[https://www.defensenews.com/land/2020/03/06/army-takes-40-mile-shots-from-extended-range-cannon-in-demo/ US Army takes 40-mile shots from extended-range cannon in demo]. ''Defense News''. 6 March 2020.</ref> The ERCA was determined to not be viable.<ref>{{Cite web|last=|first=|date=14 May 2024|title=Feature: US Army's race for new howitzers, munitions takes off after modernisation effort scuttled|url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/feature-us-armys-race-for-new-howitzers-munitions-takes-off-after-modernisation-effort-scuttled|access-date=|website=[[Janes Information Services]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240518210719/https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/feature-us-armys-race-for-new-howitzers-munitions-takes-off-after-modernisation-effort-scuttled|archive-date=18 May 2024|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>[https://www.defensenews.com/land/2024/10/15/why-the-army-is-looking-abroad-to-close-a-widening-artillery-gun-gap/ Why the Army is looking abroad to close a widening artillery gun gap]. ''[[Defense News]]''. 15 October 2024.</ref>
* '''M777C1''' – M777 with DGMS (Canada)<ref>{{cite web |last=Government of Canada |first=National Defence |date=12 March 2015 |title=ARCHIVED - Defence Acquisition Guide 2016 |url=http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/business-defence-acquisition-guide-2016/services-521.page |website=www.forces.gc.ca |access-date=16 May 2022 |archive-date=15 September 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220915081020/http://www.forces.gc.ca/en/business-defence-acquisition-guide-2016/services-521.page |url-status=dead }}</ref>

